{"parse":{"title":"house","pageid":8407,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|House}}\n==English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=building|:inh|enm:hous<id:house>|tree=1}}\n{{wikidata lexeme|L512}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*(s)kewH-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|hous}}, {{m|enm|hus}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hūs|t=dwelling, shelter, house}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hūs}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hūsą|t=house}}, possibly from {{der|en|ine-pro|*(s)kews-}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*(s)kewH-|t=to cover, hide}}. More at {{l|en|hose}}.\n\nEclipsed non-native {{noncog|enm|mees}}, {{m|enm|meson}}, {{m|enm|measoun|t=house}}, borrowed from {{noncog|xno|mes}}, {{m|fro|mies}}, {{m|fro|meis}}, {{m|fro|maisun|t=house}}. The uncommon plural form ''housen'' is from {{inh|en|enm|husen}}, {{m|enm|housen}}. (The Old English nominative plural was simply {{m|ang|hūs}}.)\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|hoose}}, {{m|sco|oos|t=house}}, {{cog|yol|heouse}}, {{m|yol|houze}}, {{m|yol|howze|t=house}}, {{cog|frr|hüs|t=house}}, {{cog|stq|Huus}}, {{m|stq|Húus|t=house}}, {{cog|fy|hûs|t=house}}, {{cog|gsw|hous}}, {{m|gsw|hus}}, {{m|gsw|husch}}, {{m|gsw|hüs}}, {{m|gsw|hüüsch|t=house}}, {{cog|bar|-}}, {{cog|cim|-}}, {{cog|mhn|haus|t=house}}, {{cog|gmw-cfr|Haus}}, {{m|gmw-cfr|Hous}}, {{m|gmw-cfr|Huus|t=home}}, {{cog|nl|huis|t=house}}, {{cog|nds-nl|hoes}}, {{m|nds-nl|huus|t=house}}, {{cog|de|Haus}}, {{m|de|Hauß|t=house}}, {{cog|nds-de|Huus|t=house}}, {{cog|li|hoes}}, {{m|li|Huus|t=house}}, {{cog|lb|Haus|t=house}}, {{cog|wym|haojs}}, {{m|wym|haus}}, {{m|wym|hoüz|t=house}}, {{cog|yi|הויז|t=house}}, {{cog|da,nb,nn,sv|hus|t=house}}, {{cog|ovd|aus|t=house}}, {{cog|fo,is|hús|t=house}}, {{cog|gme-cgo|hus|t=house}}; also {{cog|kw|kudha|t=to conceal, hide}}, {{cog|cy|cuddio|t=to hide}}, {{cog|la|cutis|t=human skin; hide, leather}}, {{cog|grc|κεύθω|t=to cover, hide}}, {{cog|xto|kāc|t=hide, skin}}, {{cog|sa|स्कुनाति|t=to cover}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|en|hoose||Northumbrian}}\n* {{alt|en|houss||obsolete}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhaʊ̯s/|[ˈhaʊ̯s]|a=RP,GA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-house-noun.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-house.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhæʊ̯s/|[ˈhæʊ̯s]|a=Southern US,Midland US,Mid-Atlantic US,NYC,AU,NZ,[[w:Fronting (sound change)|/aʊ̯/-fronting]]}}\n* {{a|en|CA|Canadian raising}}\n**  {{IPA|en|/ˈhɐʊ̯s/|[ˈhɐʊ̯s]|;|/ˈhɜʊ̯s/|;|[ˈhɜʊ̯s]|;|/ˈhʌʊ̯s/|[ˈhʌʊ̯s]|;|/ˈhəʊ̯s/|[ˈhəʊ̯s]}}\n*** {{audio|en|En-ca-raising-house.ogg|a=CA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhaːs/|a=Pittsburgh,ZA,[[w:Monophthongization|/aʊ̯/-monophthongization]]}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhʌʉ̯s/|[ˈhʌʉ̯s]|a=Scotland}}\n* {{a|en|IE}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈhɛʊ̯s/|[ˈhɛʊ̯s]|a=Standard Irish,Dublin}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈhɐʏ̯s/|[ˈhɐʏ̯s]|a=Ulster}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈhɐʊ̯s/|[ˈhɐʊ̯s]|a=Munster,Cork}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈhuːs/|[ˈhuːs]|a=Geordie}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊs|s=1}}\n* {{hyph|en|house}}\n\n====Noun====\n[[File:Niigata NCM Peasant Rice Farmers House.jpg|thumb|The '''house''' of a Japanese rice farmer]]\n[[File:9, Strada Spătarului, Bucharest (Romania).jpg|thumb|A city-'''house'''. In this photo, its garden does not appear]]\n{{en-noun|~|s|housen<l:dialectal>|hice<l:chiefly,humorous>}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|structure as abode of human beings}} A structure built or serving as an [[abode]] of human beings. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|This is my '''house''' and my family's ancestral home.}}\n#* {{RQ:Marshall Squire's Daughter|III\n|passage=The big '''houses''', and there are a good many of them, lie for the most part in what may be called by courtesy the valleys. You catch a glimpse of them sometimes at a little distance from the [railway] line, which seems to have shown some ingenuity in avoiding them,{{nb...}}.}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=1|passage=Pretty soon I struck into a sort of path&nbsp;{{nb...}}. It twisted and turned,{{...}}and opened out into a big clear space like a lawn. And, back of the lawn, was a big, old-fashioned '''house''', with piazzas stretching in front of it, and all blazing with lights. 'Twas the '''house''' I'd seen the roof of from the beach.}}\n## {{lb|en|Hong Kong|only used in names}} An [[apartment building]] within a [[public]] [[housing estate]].\n# {{senseid|en|container}} A container; a thing which houses another.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Science in the Kitchen: A Scientific Treatise on Food Substances and Their Dietetic Properties, Together with a Practical Explanation of the Principles of Healthful Cookery, and a Large Number of Original, Palatable, and Wholesome Recipes|passage=The purposes of food are to promote growth, to supply force and heat, and to furnish material to repair the waste which is constantly taking place in the body. Every breath, every thought, every motion, wears out some portion of the delicate and wonderful '''house''' in which we live.|year=1892|author=w:Ella Eaton Kellogg|page=25|pageurl=https://www.google.ca/books/edition/Science_in_the_Kitchen/97tGAQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&pg=PA25|chapter=Foods|publisher=Health Publishing Company|location=Michigan|edition=Revised|url=https://www.google.ca/books/edition/Science_in_the_Kitchen/97tGAQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=0}}\n# {{senseid|en|housing}} {{lb|en|uncountable}} Size and quality of residential accommodations; [[housing#Noun|housing]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|title=When Will the Slump End?|work=Newsweek|date=Nov 6, 2007|passage=Those homeowners who bought too much '''house''', or borrowed against inflated values are now going to be liable for their own poor decisions.}}\n# {{senseid|en|building for single household residence}} A building intended to contain a single household, as opposed to an [[apartment]] or [[condominium]] or building containing these.\n#: {{cot|en|apartment|condo|condominium|flat}}\n# {{senseid|en|household}} The people who live in a house; a [[household]]. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n#* {{RQ:KJV|Acts|10|2|passage=one that feared God with all his '''house'''}}\n# {{senseid|en|building housing something other than humans}} A [[building]] used for something other than a [[residence]] {{q|typically with qualifying word}}. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The former carriage '''house''' had been made over into a guest '''house'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|On arriving at the zoo, we immediately headed for the [[monkey house|monkey '''house''']].}}\n## {{senseid|en|place of business, company, organization}} A place of [[business]]; a company or organisation, especially a [[printing press]], a [[publishing]] company, or a [[couturier]]. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n##: {{ux|en|A small publishing '''house''' would have a contract with an independent fulfillment '''house'''.}}\n##* {{RQ:Dickens Little Dorrit|passage=I have a good banker in this city, but I would not wish to draw upon the '''house''' until the time when I shall draw for a round sum.}}\n## {{senseid|en|place of public accommodation or entertainment}} A place of public accommodation or entertainment, especially a [[public house]], an [[inn]], a [[restaurant]], a [[theatre]], or a [[casino]]; or the management thereof. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n##: {{ux|en|One more, sir, then I'll have to stop serving you – rules of the '''house''', I'm afraid.}}\n##: {{ux|en|The '''house''' always wins.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1964|title=Northwest Ohio Quarterly|volume=36|page=185|passage=The farce comedy which followed, ''When We're Married'' by Charles Burnham, was heartily praised, with the character man singled out for special extollation. The production filled the '''house'''.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=27 Aug 77|volume=5|number=8|journal=Gay Community News|page=9|author=Steve Savage;Susan \"Suki\" Eagan|title=Everything You Wanted to Know About Suki, But Were Too Distracted In Chaps to Ask Her|text=Frazier and Gary worked for me for free — for six months — they didn't take any money from the '''house'''. They worked for tips.}}\n## {{lb|en|historical}} A [[workhouse]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|title=Reports from the Commissioners|passage=To this the pauper replied that he did not want that, and that rather than be sent to the '''house''' he would look out for work.|year=1834|author=Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons|page=169|volume=29}}\n# The audience for a live theatrical or similar performance. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|After her swan-song, there wasn't a dry eye in the '''house'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Orczy Miss Elliott|story=The Affair at the Novelty Theatre|chapter=2|passage=Miss Phyllis Morgan, as the hapless heroine dressed in the shabbiest of clothes, appears in the midst of a gay and giddy throng; she apostrophises all and sundry there, including the villain, and has a magnificent scene which always brings down the '''house''', and nightly adds to her histrionic laurels.}}\n# {{lb|en|politics}} A building where a deliberative assembly meets; whence the assembly itself, particularly a component of a [[legislature]]. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The petition was so ridiculous that the '''house''' rejected it after minimal debate.}}\n# A [[dynasty]]; a family with its [[ancestor]]s and [[descendant]]s, especially a royal or noble one. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|A curse lay upon the '''House''' of Atreus.}}\n# {{lb|en|metaphorical}} A place of [[rest]] or [[repose]]. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n#* {{RQ:Jonson Every Man in His Humour|text=Like a pestilence, it doth infect / The '''houses''' of the brain.}}\n#* {{RQ:Scott Lord of the Isles|text=Such hate was his, when his last breath / Renounced the peaceful '''house''' of death {{nb...}}.}}\n# A [[grouping]] of [[schoolchildren]] for the purposes of competition in sports and other activities. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I was a member of Spenser '''house''' when I was at school.}}\n# An [[animal]]'s [[shelter]] or [[den]], or the shell of an animal such as a [[snail]], used for protection. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n# {{lb|en|astrology}} One of the twelve divisions of an astrological chart. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Religion and the Decline of Magic|passage=Since there was a limited number of planets, '''houses''' and signs of the zodiac, the astrologers tended to reduce human potentialities to a set of fixed types and to postulate only a limited number of possible variations.|year=1971|author=[[w:en:Keith Thomas (historian)|Sir Keith Vivian Thomas]]|page=313|isbn=978-0-14-013744-6|year_published=2012|publisher=[[w:en:Folio Society|The Folio Society]]}}\n# {{lb|en|cartomancy}} The fourth [[Lenormand]] card.\n# {{lb|en|chess|now|rare}} A [[square]] on a [[chessboard]], regarded as the proper place of a [[piece]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}\n# {{lb|en|curling}} The four [[concentric]] circles where points are scored on the [[ice]]. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n# [[lotto|Lotto]]; [[bingo]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}} A [[child]]ren's [[game]] in which the players [[pretend]] to be members of a [[household]].\n#: {{ux|en|As the babysitter, Emma always acted as the mother whenever the kids demanded to play '''house'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|US|dialect}} A small [[stand]] of [[tree]]s in a [[swamp]].\n# {{lb|en|sudoku}} A set of cells in a [[sudoku]] puzzle which must contain each digit exactly once, such as a row, column, or 3×3 box.\n# {{lb|en|American football|slang|with “the”}} The [[end zone]].\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{s|establishment}} {{l|en|shop}}\n* {{s|company or organisation}} {{l|en|shop}}\n\n=====Hypernyms=====\n* {{l|en|building}}\n* {{l|en|dwelling}}, {{l|en|residence}}\n\n=====Hyponyms=====\n{{col4|en\n|alehouse\n|auction house\n|backhouse\n|basket house\n|birdhouse\n|boathouse\n|boghouse\n|bog-house\n|bottle house\n|chapter house\n|coffee house\n|common house|Commons House\n|cophouse|skookum house\n|country house\n|doghouse\n|doll's house\n|dosshouse\n|doss-house\n|dreamhouse\n|dream house\n|flophouse,flop-house\n|frame house\n|full house\n|glasshouse\n|God's house\n|Government House\n|Greek house\n|greenhouse\n|grow house\n|guesthouse\n|guest-house\n|guest house\n|halfway house\n|haunted house\n|house museum\n|house of assembly\n|House of Commons\n|house of correction\n|house of detention\n|house of God\n|house of ill fame\n|house of ill repute\n|House of Lords\n|house of office\n|Houses of Parliament\n|house of worship\n|icehouse\n|jakeshouse\n|lighthouse\n|little house\n|longhouse,long-house,long house\n|lower house\n|meetinghouse,meeting-house,meeting house\n|morthouse\n|move house\n|outhouse\n|playhouse,play-house,play house\n|poorhouse\n|prisonhouse\n|privy house\n|public house\n|publishing house\n|pumphouse\n|pump house\n|royal house\n|safehouse\n|schoolhouse\n|school house\n|scouthouse\n|shithouse\n|shophouse\n|siegehouse\n|springhouse\n|storehouse\n|tea house\n|tiny house\n|town house\n|toy house\n|tribal house\n|upper house\n|warehouse\n|wartime house\n|weather house\n|Wendy house\n|White House\n|whorehouse\n}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en||orphan house|orphaned house|punk house|acceptance house\n|accepting house\n|accommodation house\n|acid house|operetta house\n|action house\n|a house divided against itself cannot stand\n|a house is not a home\n|airhouse\n|alehouse\n|ale-house\n|alms-house\n|almshouse\n|ambient house\n|animal house\n|apartment house\n|Archie Bunker house\n|armshouse||house advantage|house cut|house take|packed house\n|art-house,art house\n|audit house\n|automated clearing house\n|baby-house|crimp house||plank house\n|back house,back-house,backhouse|skeleton in one's house\n|back of house\n|baghouse\n|bakehouse\n|balti house\n|Baltimore house\n|barrelhouse|mask house|Tecla house|woman of the house\n|basket-house|house agent\n|bath-house,bathhouse\n|bat house\n|bawdy house,bawdy-house\n|bawdy-house bottle\n|beachhouse,beach house\n|Beck Houses\n|beef house,beef-house,beefhouse\n|beehouse|house dust mite|house god|house of mercy|house snake|lich-house,lych-house\n|beerhouse\n|bellhouse\n|bet the house\n|big as a house\n|big house\n|bighouse\n|big room house\n|birdhouse\n|birthhouse\n|black-house\n